146. WE are to observe, that when DIONYSIUS HALYCARNASSAEUS says, that if we regard the ancient walls of *Rome*, the extent of that city will not appear greater than that of *Athens*; he must mean the ACROPOLIS and high town only. No ancient author ever speaks of the PYRAEUM, PHALERUS, and MUNYCHIA, as the same with *Athens*. Much less can it be supposed, that DIONYSIUS would consider the matter in that light, after the walls of CIMON and *Pericles* were destroyed, and *Athens* was entirely separated from these other towns. This observation destroys all VOSSIUS's reasonings, and introduces common sense into these calculations.

